ed fundamental challenges that influenced its transition to the more public, inclusive, and vernacular discourse of the Enlightenment. Transforming the Republic of Letters is a cultural and intellectual history that chronicles this transition to "modernity" from the perspective of the internationally renowned scholar Pierre-Daniel Huet (1630-1721). Under Shelford's direction, Huet guides us into the intensely social intellectual worldof salons, scientific academies, and literary academies, while his articulate critiques illumine a combative world of Cartesians versus anti-Cartesians, ancients versus moderns, Jesuits versus Jansenists, and salonnières versus humanist scholars. Transforming the Republic of Letters raises questions of critical importance in Huet's era, and our own, about defining, sharing, and controlling access to knowledge. April G. Shelford is Assistant Professor in the History Department at American University, Washington, D.C.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 17th Century.2bisacsh  aAccess to Knowledge.  aCartesians.  aCultural History.  aEarly Modern Europe.  aEnlightenment.  aIntellectual Transformation.  aInternational Networks.  aJesuits.  aKnowledge.  aPierre-Daniel Huet.  aRepublic of Letters.  aSalon Culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046689940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580466899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580466899/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles